		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28857583">I somewhat agree with Nagisa in that plot holes don't deter enjoyment to a large extent in some shows. These aren't necessarily "over the top" or run on cartoon logic; I think it depends on what the focus of the show is. An example is the Steins;Gate movie, which is probably jumbled with plotholes in addition to being dead serious. But since the movie's primary purpose is to further develop relationships between characters rather than showcasing cool time traveling, the plot holes can be forgiven. <div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>Not to mention that the time traveling is such a pile of interpretable crap that you can never be sure whether there is a plot hole, as 10 other people will then come up with 11 different theories to explain why it's logically consistent. Who in their right minds watch Steins;Gate for time traveling anyway? They put so much effort into explaining something which has no scientific consistency whatsoever. <!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
Of course, detecting any plot hole while watching a show breaks immersion. Plotholes can be forgiven only if they're next to unnoticable unless examined carefully (if it's extremely minor or too complex). I don't agree with the example of Code Geass though. It relies on the characters' tactical expertise for a large chunk of its enjoyment, and the lapse in judgement shown by many of them really do take away from the enjoyment (though I still love it). <br />
<br />
Nevertheless, whereas plotholes sometimes don't detract from enjoyment, they still make the shows objectively worse. Not much to say or argue about here except for the pointless argument of whether objective evaluations are possible or relevant.<br />
<br />
An exception to the above is when plot holes are used consciously in shows. This can be seen in comedies such as Teekyu where absurdities are utilized for comical effect. Another example is Gurren Lagann, which consciously breaks logic to do the impossible and see the invisible. The problem here is whether intended "plot holes" can even be considered plot holes anymore.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
