		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28860091">I don't agree with the Uchouten Kazoku example seeing as it wasn't a "plot-hole", it was the justification he used to eat animals. Love does bizarre things to most people and they often go about expressing it in many different ways, whether they seem rationally justified or not. <br />
<br />
Ultimately I think it comes down to what can be considered a plot hole or not. There are anime/manga that seem like they have several unexplained "plot holes" only for them to pull a fast one and explain them and potentially blow your mind with them. It usually comes down to their intended purpose.<br />
<br />
That's not to say that all plot holes are like that, several anime and manga finish up with absolutely no explanation to any of their plot holes and that does actively derail the experience. Then there's the issue of adaptation induced plot holes, with Berserk rushing to the front of my mind. With the absence of the Skull Knight in the anime, how exactly does Guts survive the Eclipse? There's no explanation given to it. Granted, reading the manga rectifies this but it's an issue that managed to hamper my experience with the anime of Berserk and completely ruined my immersion. <br />
<br />
What about filler induced plot holes as well? Long running shounen shows usually have this issue, and in the writers' haste to extend the storyline in order to fill for time whilst the source material continues, they usually show up. One Piece had a couple of odd plot holes that were strictly anime only and the manga isn't too kind on them as a result.<br />
<br />
Yeah, plot holes are odd.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
