		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28872909">Code Geass.<br />
<br />
Just to throw one more into the batch. like, who even watched CG for a realistic depiction of a superhuman, precocious teenager conquering the universe via a green head alien girl who just so happens to grant him some strange will. From episode one and its reputation, I expected nothing out of CG but bombast. And am I to complain because there wasn't more? that would be ludicrous. <br />
<br />
Plot holes are usually caused in consequence to Deus ex Machina, and while those are sometimes forgivable, there is an extent to which it gets excessive. There is a common misconception, though, that things unexplained automatically equate to plot holes. While it does mean that the work will be less concrete and more interpretable, occasionally it adds to... the experience. Ambiguity and obfuscations can be good, and it really depends on the work and its purpose of using cryptic things. Just because something wasn't definitively incorporated into the story doesn't necessarily make it nonexistent; it could be implied or strongly hinted at. Again, it really depends.<br />
<br />
I love Steins Gate beyond a universe above the infinite stratus of earth, but it simply isn't discernible to say that there aren't as many holes as there are times that Mayoii says "Tuturu~" or even Kurisu blushing. This is because SG analyzes time travel in a manner which doesn't match up with the empirical evidences of quantum physics thus far. Perhaps in the near future these plot holes will be substantiated and "legitimized". But for now they remain to be thought-provoking albeit unscientific elements of SG. Sci Fi in general struggles with this, and that's because Sci Fi mostly seeks to explore the potentials or consequences of technology, and not what it's already capable of.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
