		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28908549">Another person here agreeing with the Code Geass comparison.<br />
I love Code Geass to bits and pieces; it's my gateway show, dealt with a lot of themes, has a relatively solid plot and a fantastic cast of characters (I'll never, EVER get sick of Lelouch casting Geass. Seriously, you have no idea how many times I'd come back in a bad mode, open my laptop and watch him do that, making my day way better in the process).<br />
<br />
But part of why I loved Code Geass so much, which I often connect to why we often ignore moments of questionable writing in shows, is that if a show connects to us, or delivers a message we can relate to and connect to, then we can ignore all sorts of flaws (in this case plot holes) a show would have. Guilty Crown is an example of a series that tried to be what Code Geass was to a lot of people. And yet, people were more harsh on Guilty Crown and constantly openly ridiculing the show, in-spite of it suffering from some of the VERY SAME problems as Code Geass in its plot. Some people would use being overly entertaining as an argument, but I feel that any show which succeeds in getting its message or appealing in its message to a wide audience is more likely to be loved than a show which doesn't.<br />
