		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28939527">Plot holes really bother me. So I try super-hard to fill them up. <br />
<br />
For example, if I watch an anime episode and a character's actions don't make sense, I think for a long time and come up with a lengthy justification on why the character would act that way. If it's something that isn't logical in our universe, I make sure to fill in the rest of the anime universe so that everything works out. With research and a ton of roundabout thinking, however, most plot holes can be filled, so after proper justification, I don't mind them too much. However, any plot holes end up to be very time consuming with this method, so I always prefer my anime without. Unfortunately, it's practically impossible to have a good scifi or supernatural anime without some plot holes... only then can the anime blow your mind.<br />
<br />
Let me use the example of "I love animals so I want to eat them." There is, of course, the explanation that love is a strange thing. But in case that's not enough, I'd say that the world is a cruel place to animals, so eating them is like putting them out of misery, so the character loves animals, and has this somewhat twisted logic, so wants to eat animals. </div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/animelist/einonymous&amp;sclick=1"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://myanimelist.net/signature/einonymous.png" /></a> </div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
