		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28944383">I think it's worth discussing the definition of "plot hole," because there seems to be some disagreement within this thread over what a plot hole is.  My own view is as follows:<br />
<br />
Ambiguity is not a plot hole.  Intentionally withholding information from the audience is not a plot hole.  Leaving unanswered questions at the end of a show is not a plot hole.  In fact, a good story will nearly always have moments of ambiguity, moments where it does not lay all of its cards on the table.<br />
<br />
So what is a plot hole?  A plot hole can most simply be described as a contradiction.  Some contradictions are overt, such as a character breaking both legs, and then somehow managing to sprint away immediately shortly after.  Some contradictions are a bit more subtle, such as someone behaving out of character.  And omissions can often point to an inconsistency of character.<br />
<br />
For example, one common "plot hole" complaint I hear is "There was an easy way to solve the problem, and the characters didn't choose the easy solution."  That in and of itself is not a contradiction.  However, "The main character is portrayed as a brilliant mastermind who accounts for every contingency, but he somehow managed to ignore the easy solution" <em>is</em> a contradiction, because what we know about the character (his brilliant mind) contradicts the events of the story (he somehow misses the obvious solution).  It's perfectly valid for the story to address this with an explanation, such as "The character was so caught up in his more complicated plans and in love with his own genius machinations that arrogance made him oblivious to the obvious solution."  But to offer no explanation for why a rational actor would ignore an easy solution that is obvious to the viewer is a contradiction, albeit a non-explicit one.<br />
<br />
Going by my own definition, I consider plot holes unforgivable.  And if you look at examples of "cartoon logic" like Kill la Kill, you'll notice that they are internally consistent.  Yeah, KLK is pretty ridiculous, but it establishes pretty clear rules for things like how the clothing works and sticks to them.  Even late revelations are presented as, "Things were always this way; they contradict your current understanding, but that's because your prior understanding was incomplete," and usually implicit in that understanding is why the old paradigm was incomplete.  Even an outlandish show like Nichijou has its own rules, making it easy to hand-wave things like the fact that a small child possesses the brilliance required to construct a fully-functional android.  Note that while Nichijou does not allow you to expect the universe at large to behave in a predictable manner, the characters generally do behave in a predictable manner: Yuko is a lazy spaz, Mai is quiet and has a rather eccentric brand of humor, the professor behaves like a young child, etc.  Thus, it is perfect acceptable for Nano's arm to pop off and reveal wheat chaff, but it would be unacceptable for Mai to engage in a chatty conversation about her interest in fashion and complain about the fact that she doesn't have boyfriend.  It doesn't matter whether the show follows real-world logic; all that is necessary is that it obey its own logic.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
